<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888300014&r=1&w=2">Mail from unregistered hosts</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837783700019&r=1&w=2">Jon Solomon &lt;JSOL () BUCS20 ! BU ! EDU&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198605">1986-05-06 23:29:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026707&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026707&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

We have this problem at BU because only one of our 6 class C networks
is advertized. Any host not on the advertized must point to one that
is. Fortunately for us this is a fairly simple change to our mail
software (fiddling creatively with the sendmail.cf), and I suspect
in most workstations it is fairly simple to add this hack only to
remove it when everybody is running domains.

I claim that there are really only two "timestamps" we have to
worry about:

	Now
	When all internet hosts run domains. (MILNET or otherwise).

I further claim that the user%workstation@nic-registered host (or in 
our case "advertized host") is only needed until domains are fully
implemented across the Internet.

--JSol

